{{Infobox language |name=Kim |nativename= |states=[[Chad]] |speakers={{sigfig|15400|2}} |date=1993 census |ref=e18 |familycolor=Niger-Congo |fam2=[[Atlantic–Congo languages|Atlantic–Congo]] |fam3=[[Mbum–Day languages|Mbum–Day]] |fam4=[[Kim languages]] |dia1=Garap |dia2=Gerep |dia3=Kolop |dia4=Kosop |iso3=kia |glotto=kimm1246 |glottorefname=Kim }}
'''Kim''' of southern [[Chad]] is an [[Mbum–Day languages|Mbum language]] spoken by 15,000 people. It is one of the three members of the [[Kim languages]] group, together with [[Besme language|Besme]] and [[Goundo language|Goundo]].
The language was once mistakenly classified as [[Chadic language|Chadic]], and called ''[[Masa language|Masa]]'', a Chadic name.
There is strong dialectical divergence; Blench considers Garap (Éré), Gerep (Djouman, Jumam), Kolop (Kilop, Kolobo), and Kosop (Kwasap, Kim) to be distinct languages.<ref> Roger Blench, 2004. [http://www.rogerblench.info/Language/Niger-Congo/AU/Adamawa%20language%20list.pdf List of Adamawa languages] (ms) </ref>
==References== {{Reflist}}
[[Category:Languages of Chad]] [[Category:Adamawa languages]]
