{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}} {{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}} {{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] --> | name = U. K. Kumaran | pseudonym = | other_name = | image = Uk kumaran.jpg | birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1950|05|11}} | birth_place = [[Payyoli]], [[Kozhikode]], Kerala | occupation = Writer, journalist | language = [[Malayalam]] | alma_mater = [[Zamorin's Guruvayurappan College|Zamorin's Guruvayurappan College, Kozhikode]] | nationality = Indian | genre = Novel, short story, essays | subject = | notableworks = | movement = | influences = | influenced = | spouse = | awards = [[Kerala Sahitya Akademi Award]] | website = }} '''U. K. Kumaran''' ({{lang-ml|യു.കെ. കുമാരന്‍}}; born 11 May 1950) is a [[Malayalam]]-language novelist, [[short story writer]], essayist and journalist from [[Kerala]], India. He is a recipient of the [[Kerala Sahitya Akademi Award]] and [[Vayalar Award]].<ref>[http://origin-www.mathrubhumi.com/english/story.php?id=128253 "UK Kumaran felicitated"]. ''[[Mathrubhumi]]''. 17 September 2012. Retrieved 13 June 2013.</ref>
==Biography== Kumaran was born in [[Payyoli]], [[Kozhikode]] on 11 May 1950.{{Citation needed|date= April 2018}} He studied at Government AUP School, Kizhoor and Government High School, Payyoli. He obtained a degree in economics from [[Zamorin's Guruvayurappan College|Guruvayurappan College, Kozhikode]] and a diploma in Journalism and Public Relations.{{Citation needed|date= April 2018}}
He started his career as a journalist, in ''Veekshanam Vaarika'' as Assistant Editor. Later he joined ''[[Kerala Kaumudi]]'' and worked as its Kozhikode unit chief.{{Citation needed|date= April 2018}} He has held numerous posts including the State Vice-President of Kerala Pathrapravarthaka Union, Member of Kerala State Telephone Advisory Committee, Member of [[Calicut University]] Journalism Board of Studies, Vice-Chairman of [[Kerala Sahitya Akademi]], Advisory committee member of National Book Trust and the director of Navakerala Co-operative Publishing House.{{Citation needed|date= April 2018}}
He began his literary career with a short story "Chalanam" at the age of 17. The story emerged around people whose lives and livelihood revolved around movie announcements being made with drum beats in the Payyoli market.{{Citation needed|date= April 2018}}
According to the Hindu newspaper: "It is a comprehensive landscape, peopled with characters and nature. Each character should grow and reach a point where they move towards a climax well. You cannot leave them mid-way, unfinished."<ref>P. Anima (4 August 2012). [http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-metroplus/matters-of-the-mind/article3724888.ece "Matters of the mind"]. ''[[The Hindu]]''. Retrieved 13 June 2013.</ref>
==Awards== Kumaran has received numerous awards and recognitions including the [[Kerala Sahitya Akademi Award]] for ''Policukarante Penmakkal'' (2011) and Vaikom Chandrasekharan Nair Award for ''Thakshankunnu Swaroopam'' (2012).<ref>[http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/sahitya-akademi-awards-announced/article3715418.ece "Sahitya Akademi awards announced"]. ''The Hindu''. 2 August 2012. Retrieved 13 June 2013.</ref><ref>[http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-kerala/award-for-uk-kumaran/article4566352.ece "Award for U.K. Kumaran"]. ''The Hindu''. 31 March 2013. Retrieved 13 June 2013.</ref>
