{{Infobox language |name=Volow |altname=Valuwa |nativename=Aplow |states=[[Vanuatu]] |region=[[Mota Lava]] island, [[Banks Islands]] |extinct=1986 |ref=<ref name="IJSL"/> |familycolor=Austronesian |fam2=[[Malayo-Polynesian languages|Malayo-Polynesian]] |fam3=[[Oceanic languages|Oceanic]] |fam4=[[Southern Oceanic languages|Southern Oceanic]] |fam5=Vanuatu |fam6=[[Northern Vanuatu languages|Northern Vanuatu]] |fam7=[[East Vanuatu languages|East Vanuatu]] |fam8=[[Mwotlap language|Mwotlap]] |isoexception=dialect |glotto=volo1238 |glottorefname=Volow }}
'''Volow''' (pronounced {{IPA-xx|βʊˈlʊw|}}; formerly known as ''Valuwa'' or ''Valuga'') is an [[Oceanic languages|Oceanic]] language variety which used to be spoken in the area of [[Aplow]], in the eastern part of the island of [[Motalava]], in [[Vanuatu]].<ref>[http://alex.francois.free.fr/AF-field.htm#Vanuatu List of Banks islands languages].</ref>
==Sociolinguistics== Volow has [[Language shift|receded]] historically in favour of the now dominant language [[Mwotlap language|Mwotlap]].<ref name="IJSL">{{Harvcoltxt|François|2012|p=87}}</ref> It is now only remembered by a single passive speaker, who lives in the village of [[Aplow]] — the new name of what was previously known as Volow.
The similarity of Volow with Mwotlap is such that the two communalects may be considered [[dialect]]s of a single language.
==Phonology== Volow, like Mwotlap, has 7 [[phoneme|phonemic]] vowels, which are all short [[monophthong]]s:<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|François|2005a|p=445}}.</ref><ref name="LingTyp" /> {|class="wikitable" !&nbsp; ! [[Front vowel|Front]] ! [[Back vowel|Back]] |- ![[Close vowel|Close]] | align=center | {{IPA|i}} | align=center | {{IPA|u}} |- ![[Near-close vowel|Near-close]] | align=center | {{IPA|ɪ}} | align=center | {{IPA|ʊ}} |- ![[Open-mid vowel|Open-mid]] | align=center | {{IPA|ɛ}} | align=center | {{IPA|ɔ}} |- ![[Open vowel|Open]] | colspan="2" style="text-align:center;"| {{IPA|a}} |}
The language also has a typologically rare consonant: a [[labialization|rounded]], [[prenasalization|prenasalised]] [[voiced labial-velar plosive]] {{IPA|[ᵑᵐɡ͡bʷ]}}:<ref name="LingTyp">{{Harvcoltxt|François|2005b|p=116}}.</ref> e.g. {{IPA|[n.lɛᵑᵐɡ͡bʷɛβɪn]}} “woman”<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|François|2013|p=191}}.</ref> (spelled ''n-le'''q̄'''evēn'' in the local orthography).
==External links== * [http://lacito.vjf.cnrs.fr/pangloss/corpus/show_text_en.php?id=crdo-VLW_ORPHELIN_SOUND&idref=crdo-VLW_ORPHELIN A story in Volow presented in bilingual (Volow–French) format, with audio recording] <small>(taken from the ''[[Pangloss Collection]]'' of CNRS-[[LACITO]])</small>. This story was recorded by anthropologist Bernard Vienne in 1969 from the last fluent speaker Wanhand [†1986], and was translated by linguist [[Alexandre François|A. François]] in 2003, with the help of Wanhand's son.
